  <h2>What is whole step down (D standard)?</h2>
  <p>
    Every string drops a whole step: D–G–C–F–A–D. All your chord shapes work
    unchanged — everything just sounds two frets lower. It's a favorite for
    heavier tones (early metal lives here), for easing tension on a stiff
    guitar, and for matching singers who want songs a step lower.
  </p>
  <h2>How to tune a whole step down</h2>
  <p>
    Tap start and go string by string from thickest to thinnest — each one
    needs to come down, so the tuner will read "too high" and point you at the
    right peg to loosen. A whole step is a decent turn of the peg; go slow and
    let the note settle before you judge the needle. Six checkmarks and you're
    in D standard.
  </p>
  <p>
    Only want the low string dropped? That's <a href="/drop-d">Drop D</a> —
    and if you want this tuning with the low string dropped further, that's
